Computational Essay

Author

Marzhan Nuraly

Introduction

The number of tourists and overseas employees in the Bay area increasing every year. Due to population rise, planning of city infrastructure is becoming popular in California State.

In this computational essay, we will summarize and visualize data for tourist and citizen usage, including the AirBnb dataset, and data classification by socio-economic variables from Census API. Moreover, regionalisation city of San Francisco by land usage and economic purpose.

Airbnb in the BAY AREA at Neighbourhood Level

Data pre-processing

The Airbnb dataset for 3 cities, San Francisco, San Mateo, Oakland. The analysis of the dataset gives opportunities to make a summary of tourism and economic analysis for the region. The data pre-processing method for outlier identification was applied.

listings_SanFran <- read.csv("data/SanFrancisco/listings.csv")

# REMOVE OUTLIERS

listings_SanFran <- listings_SanFran %>%
  mutate(z_score = (number_of_reviews - mean(number_of_reviews)) / sd(number_of_reviews))

threshold <- 3

filtered_data <- listings_SanFran %>%
  filter(abs(z_score) <= threshold) %>%
  select(-z_score)

write.csv(filtered_data, "data/nooutliers/listings_nooutliers_fr.csv", row.names = FALSE)


listings_SanMateo <- read.csv("data/SanMateo/listings.csv")

listings_SanMateo <- listings_SanMateo %>%
  mutate(z_score = (number_of_reviews - mean(number_of_reviews)) / sd(number_of_reviews))

filtered_data_sn <- listings_SanMateo %>%
  filter(abs(z_score) <= threshold) %>%
  select(-z_score)


write.csv(filtered_data_sn, "data/nooutliers/listings_nooutliers_mt.csv", row.names = FALSE)


listings_Oak <- read.csv("data/Oakland/listings.csv")

listings_Oak <- listings_Oak %>%
  mutate(z_score = (number_of_reviews - mean(number_of_reviews)) / sd(number_of_reviews))

filtered_data_oa <- listings_Oak %>%
  filter(abs(z_score) <= threshold) %>%
  select(-z_score)

write.csv(filtered_data_oa, "data/nooutliers/listings_nooutliers_oa.csv", row.names = FALSE)
setwd("data/nooutliers")

csv_files <- list.files(pattern = ".csv")

df_list <- list()

for (file in csv_files) {
  df <- read.csv(file, header = TRUE)
  df_list <- append(df_list, list(df))
}

combined_df <- do.call(rbind, df_list)

write.csv(combined_df, "listings_Bay_Area.csv", row.names = FALSE)

The data of listings joined for one .csv file by the function rbind. rbind (CN, 2022) row binding, joining multiple rows into single frame.

# Read combined csv file with Bay Area listings
listings_Bay_Area <- read.csv("data/nooutliers/listings_Bay_Area.csv")

The second data used for classification is Bay Area Zip codes in the format ShapeFile from Berkeley library.

shape_BayArea <- read_sf("data/data_1/bayarea_zipcodes.shp")

shape_BayArea <- st_make_valid(shape_BayArea)

bay_zip_sorted <- shape_BayArea[shape_BayArea$PO_NAME %in% c("SAN FRANCISCO", "SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO", "OAKLAND", "SAN MATEO", "DALY CITY", "PACIFICA", "MOSS BEACH", "BURLINGAME", "HALF MOON BAY", "SAN BRUNO", "BRISBANE", "MILLBRAE", "SAN CARLOS", "PALO ALTO", "REDWOOD CITY"),]

bay_zip_sorted <- st_make_valid(bay_zip_sorted)

Spatial Join

The points were created from the longitude and latitude of listings. Then we set EPSG:4326 coordinate system because it uses coordinates to specify locations on the surface. In addition, WGS84 has a similar projected system, but EPSG:4326 is the standard coordinate system used in GIS and good for use in large areas Moreover this projection system is based on WGS84 and includes projection properties of this CRS (Coordinate Reference System). As we get points, we should join points with polygons of zip codes in the Bay Area. st_join (Wickham 2023) joining intersections by spatial relations. To get data without losing spatial objects should have similar Coordinate Reference Systems.

airbnb_sf <- listings_Bay_Area %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude", "latitude")) %>%
  st_set_crs(4326)

airbnb_sf <- st_transform(airbnb_sf, crs = st_crs(bay_zip_sorted))
# SPATIAL JOIN
listing_Bay_area_join <- st_join(bay_zip_sorted, airbnb_sf)
summary_data_1 <- listing_Bay_area_join %>%
  group_by(ZIP) %>%
  summarize(listing_count = n(), 
         average_price = mean(price))

Data classification

Choropleth maps are used for classification, this map is visually effective for large-scale values, and easy-to-interpret block shading makes it easier to understand variations. Data classification was done in quantile intervals, which arranges groups with the same quantity, and comparing them to an equal classifier gives balanced results for grouping data, which avoids having classes with outlier results and prevents null value. In quantile intervals, the number of classes is selected as 6 because distortion is minimised with a higher number of classes.

# Number of listings classification
equal_cl <- classIntervals(summary_data_1$listing_count, n = 6, style = "quantile")
summary_data_1$equal_cl <- cut(summary_data_1$listing_count, equal_cl$brks)
num_bins <- 6
cmap <- brewer.pal(num_bins, "PuRd")

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = bay_zip_sorted, fill = "white", color = "black") +
  geom_sf(data = summary_data_1, aes(fill = equal_cl), color = "black") +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = cmap,
    name = "Number of Listings",
    labels = gsub("[,]", "-", paste0(gsub("[\\[\\]()]", " ", levels(summary_data_1$equal_cl), perl = TRUE)))
  ) +
  geom_sf_text(data = summary_data_1,
               aes(label = ZIP),
               fun.geometry = sf::st_centroid, size=1) +
  labs(title = "Map 1.1. The number of Airbnb listings per Zip Code in 
                Bay Area") +
  theme_minimal()+
  annotation_scale(location = "bl", width_hint = 0.4) +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "bl", which_north = "true", 
        pad_x = unit(-0.1, "in"), pad_y = unit(0.2, "in"),
        style = north_arrow_fancy_orienteering) +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank()
  )

The choropleth map gives an output of the number of AirBnb listings. In the north of the Bay Area, the number of listings is between 317 to 772, while in Oakland side has fewer Airbnb listings. Because of using quantile intervals, we can see an area with NA that doesnât have a class in this range.

The choropleth map for the average prices of AirBnb listings to ZIP is classified by Natural break intervals. This style is the most optimal class range to classify data ânaturallyâ, where the class range is identified by similar characteristics and forms natural groups. After classification, the highest cost between 1280 dollars (1.28e+03) and 1820 dollars (1.82e+03) is in the ZIP â94192â, San Francisco. The lowest prices are in west, east and south San Francisco and Oakland. In the San Mateo country, most ZIP areas have lower average costs from 233 to 424 dollars for Airbnb.

After visualizing Bay Area Airbnb listings, San Francisco is a more popular city compared to San Mateo and Oakland. The dataset includes information about the number of reviews, descriptions, availability and room types. The potential bias of the data is that it doesnât include more information about reviews. The reviews and their ratings are necessary to make clustering of rents that will make an impact on rent representation.Â 

Socio-economic variables from the ACS data

In this section, the Bay Area is analysed with socio-economic variables from the ACS data. The purpose of this analysis is to explore the spatial distribution of variables and visualize the proportion of neighbourhoods.

# The variables of median household income and the number of employers of all races working in the rental sphere.

# MEDIAN HOUSEHOLD INCOME = B19013_001
# INDUSTRY CLASS OF WORKERS (RENTAL) = C24070_065E

bay_unit <- get_acs(
  state = "CA",
  county = c(sanfran = "San Francisco", sanmateo = "San Mateo", contracosta = "Contra Costa", alameda= "Alameda"),
  geography = "tract",
  variables = c("B19013_001", "C24070_065E"),
  geometry = TRUE,
  summary_var = "C24020_001",
  year = 2020,
  output = "wide"
)

#The main 2 variables are "B19013_001" and "C24070_065E". The data in sf form and the column names are changed for a fast understanding of their purpose.
bay_unit <- bay_unit %>%
  select(GEOID, medianIncome = B19013_001E, emp_pop = C24070_065E, summary_est) %>%
  filter(complete.cases(medianIncome))

According to (Stevens 2015), the data must be pre-processed if itâs a number unit, then the percentage must be calculated.

bay_unit <- bay_unit %>% mutate(percent = 100 * (emp_pop / summary_est))%>% select(GEOID, medianIncome, percent)

Bivariate choropleth maps giving visualization to the spatial relationship between quantitative variables (Christopher Prener, 2022). The data was classified with the Natural Breaks (Jenks) style that creates groups with similar values and maximizes the differences between groups.

bi_dd <- bi_class(bay_unit, x = percent, y = medianIncome, style = "jenks", dim = 3)

map_2 <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = bi_dd, mapping = aes(fill = bi_class), color = "white", size = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  bi_scale_fill(pal = "DkViolet", dim = 3) +
  bi_theme() +
  annotation_scale(location = "br", width_hint = 0.6) +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "br", which_north = "true", 
        pad_x = unit(1, "in"), pad_y = unit(0.2, "in"),
        style = north_arrow_fancy_orienteering) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 9, angle = 90, vjust = 1, hjust = 0)) +
  labs(caption="Median household income and % of employed population in rental,
       Bay Area (Map 2)")


legend_1 <- bi_legend(pal = "DkViolet",
                    dim = 3,
                    xlab = "Higher % of emp in rent",
                    ylab = "Higher Income ",
                    size = 6)

finalPlot <- ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(map_2, 0, 0, 1.07, 1.07) +
  draw_plot(legend_1, 0.04, 0.2, 0.3, 0.3)

finalPlot

By the classification with two dimensions, the map visualize: grey areas - low median household income and low percentage of employees in the rental. Blue areas - high household income and a low percentage of rental workers. Violet areas - high household income and high percentage of employees in rental. Red areas are low-income and high percentage of people working on rental. In the city of San Francisco, most of the areas have high incomes and a low percentage of rental workers. This classification means that in that area more homeownership can be characterised as residential neighbourhoods.

The characteristics for typology in economics, those areas described as well-being neighbourhoods. Also, this class identify the low dependence of the rental income. By analysing two data, we can indicate equal residents and rental business neighbourhoods and identify that there is a larger rental industry presence. As a result, Airbnb can be clustered as affordable and economically stable. The San Mateo country mostly has residential neighbourhoods and well-being neighbourhoods. In contrast, similar neighbourhoods and clusters can be used in Oakland.

Autocorrelation

Spatial autocorrelation stands for similarity of values of observation and similarity in locations. If adjacent data observation has similar data, then itâs positive autocorrelation, while if adjacent values have very different values itâs negative autocorrelation (Haining, 2001).

nb_q <- poly2nb(airbnb_price_inc, queen = TRUE) 
w_queen_std <- nb2listw(nb_q, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)
#STANDARDISING MEDIAN HOUSEHOLD INCOME
airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome_sd <- (airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome - mean(airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome))/sd(airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome)

Global Moranâs I was applied to check spatial autocorrelationâs existence using standardised data.

airbnb_price_inc$lg_price <- lag.listw(w_queen_std, airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome_sd)
# p-value < $\frac{1}{1 + N}$, where $N$ is the number of simulations.

MC<- moran.mc(airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome_sd, w_queen_std, nsim = 999)
MC

    Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I

data:  airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome_sd 
weights: w_queen_std  
number of simulations + 1: 1000 

statistic = 0.60368, observed rank = 1000, p-value = 0.001
alternative hypothesis: greater

The statistics of Moranâs I is calculated to test the theory that âthe median household income values is classified randomly using randomnessâ. The Monte-Carlo testing approach is used with 999 simulation numbers. p-value = 0.001 analysed that data is strongly clustered (Gimond, 2019).

lisa_perm <- localmoran_perm(airbnb_price_inc$medianIncome, w_queen_std, nsim=1000, alternative="two.sided")

quadrants <- hotspot(lisa_perm, Prname="Pr(z != E(Ii)) Sim", cutoff=0.1)

airbnb_price_inc$quadrant <- as.character(quadrants)  %>% replace_na("Non-mean")

To identify local clusters and local outliers Local Moran I applied. The hotspot() function is used to compute hot spot or outlier cutoff based on the normal distribution and p-value (Darrouzet-Nardi, 2018).

cluster_plot <- tm_shape(airbnb_price_inc) +
  tm_fill(col = "medianIncome", palette = viridisLite::viridis(6),
              style = "equal", title="Equal Cluster") +
  labs(title = "Median Income cluster")+
  tm_compass(position = c(0.01, 0.03)) +

lisa_plot <- tm_shape(airbnb_price_inc) + tm_fill(col = "quadrant", title = "",
breaks = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6),
palette =  c("#FF6927", "#5CD2D9", "#FFD117", "#FFD8C7", "lightgrey"),
labels = c("High-High", "Low-Low", "High-Low",
           "Low-High", "Non-mean")) +
tm_legend(text.size = 1)  + tm_borders(alpha = 0.5) +
tm_compass(position = c(0.01, 0.03)) + 
tm_scale_bar(position = c(0.6, 0.03)) + 
tm_layout(title = "LISA Cluster Map 4")  +
tm_legend(bg.color="grey95", frame=TRUE) + 
tm_layout(legend.outside = TRUE, inner.margins = c(0.1, 0.1, 0.02, 0.05), bg.color="aliceblue")

tmap_arrange(cluster_plot, lisa_plot, sync = TRUE, ncol = 2)

On the left side is a choropleth map that visualises an equally clustered Map of the Bay Area with median income values, the map on the right is LISAâs result for median household incomes. In the map on the right, orange zones indicate areas with high median income values and high-valued neighbours, while blue indicates low values. According to maps, San Mateo country leading with high medium incomes. The north and central areas of San Francisco also have high-income values and highly valued neighbours. On Map 1.1 and Map 1.2 These zones have more number of listings and a high average price of Airbnb. Oakland has cheaper Airbnb prices and a medium number of listings clustered to Low-High having neighbours with high value of income.

skater_results_2 <- spdep::skater(ncuts=7, edges= tree_queen_2[,1:2], data = df_std_2)

tr_in_Bay_area_join$regionalisation <- skater_results_2$groups
map_cluster_2 = tm_shape(tr_in_Bay_area_join) +
  tm_fill(col = "regionalisation", title = "Commercial Tax Regions
          Map 5", palette = plasma(256), style = "jenks") + 
  tm_borders(col = "white", lwd = .01)  + 
  tm_layout(legend.outside = TRUE, legend.position = c(0.02, 0.55)) +
  tm_compass(type = "arrow", position = c("left", "top") , size = 2) +
  tm_scale_bar(breaks = c(0,1,2,3), text.size = 0.8, position =  c("right", "top"))
tmap_arrange(map_cluster, map_cluster_2)

Map 5 is showing regionalized areas of San Francisco by city facilities and commercial vacancy taxpayersâ location. The geographical insight from regionalisation is economic activity indicating areas with commercial significance and analysis of land usage. The land usage gives a short understanding of how city parts are utilized by showing where the most recreational, commercial and residential places are located. In summary, the regionalization of cities with selected criteria is useful for infrastructure planning, especially for planning recreational areas. Moreover, with the help of identified areas, zoning regulations informing commercial active zones is one of the useful applications for urban policy as infrastructure planning for facilities.
